WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.960 --> 00:00:03.290
Prof: So today we're
going to engage Modernism.

00:00:03.290 --> 00:00:06.439
We're going to be talking
principally about the music of

00:00:06.439 --> 00:00:07.470
Igor Stravinsky.
 

00:00:07.470 --> 00:00:09.460
I should also mention Arnold
Schoenberg.

00:00:09.460 --> 00:00:15.316
Just as Verdi and Wagner were
the principal composers of opera

00:00:15.316 --> 00:00:20.097
in the nineteenth century,
so Schoenberg and Stravinsky

00:00:20.097 --> 00:00:23.987
were the principal proponents--
not only of instrumental music,

00:00:23.987 --> 00:00:26.647
but some vocal music--
in the first half of the

00:00:26.647 --> 00:00:27.810
twentieth century.
 

00:00:27.810 --> 00:00:30.974
So we want to keep them
carefully positioned on our

00:00:30.974 --> 00:00:32.240
radar screen here.
 

00:00:32.240 --> 00:00:34.954
Igor Stravinsky,
of course, was a Russian

00:00:34.954 --> 00:00:36.379
composer, born in St.
 

00:00:36.379 --> 00:00:37.330
Petersburg.
 

00:00:37.330 --> 00:00:39.410
You have the dates up there on
the board, I'm sure.

00:00:39.410 --> 00:00:44.340
He studied with Nikolai
Rimsky-Korsakov,

00:00:44.340 --> 00:00:46.540
who wrote one famous piece,
Scheherazade--

00:00:46.540 --> 00:00:48.130
which I used to hear all the
time as a kid--

00:00:48.130 --> 00:00:54.570
and then caught the eye of
Sergei Diaghilev.

00:00:54.570 --> 00:00:57.180
Serge Diaghilev was an
impresario.

00:00:57.180 --> 00:00:58.920
What's an impresario?
 

00:00:58.920 --> 00:01:02.350
Who can tell me what an
impresario is?

00:01:02.350 --> 00:01:05.049
It's a fancy word for--Thaddeus.
 

00:01:05.049 --> 00:01:05.629
Student: A producer.
 

00:01:05.629 --> 00:01:06.920
Prof: A producer. Okay.
 

00:01:06.920 --> 00:01:09.200
Think of the Broadway show
"The Producers."

00:01:09.200 --> 00:01:11.828
He's simply a producer.
 

00:01:11.828 --> 00:01:16.695
And what Diaghilev was
producing and importing into

00:01:16.695 --> 00:01:21.659
Paris from Russia was Modernist
art from Russia--

00:01:21.659 --> 00:01:24.330
Modernist painting,
Modernist ballet,

00:01:24.330 --> 00:01:28.239
Modernist art music,
and Modernist opera.

00:01:28.239 --> 00:01:31.331
So that's what we want to keep
in mind with regard to Sergei

00:01:31.331 --> 00:01:31.959
Diaghilev.
 

00:01:31.959 --> 00:01:35.180
And for Diaghilev,
Stravinsky composed,

00:01:35.180 --> 00:01:38.700
early in his career,
three important ballet scores,

00:01:38.700 --> 00:01:41.285
and you have those titles up on
the board there:

00:01:41.285 --> 00:01:43.727
Firebird with its date--
what?

00:01:43.727 --> 00:01:50.263
1909--Petrushka,
1911, and then The Rite of

00:01:50.263 --> 00:01:53.030
Spring in 1913.
 

00:01:53.030 --> 00:01:58.235
Now, the first of these ballets
to really show a heavy Modernist

00:01:58.235 --> 00:02:02.365
content is not so much
Firebird but more the

00:02:02.365 --> 00:02:06.159
second of this troika here,
Petrushka.

00:02:06.159 --> 00:02:10.639
It's modern because of the new
approach to rhythm.

00:02:10.639 --> 00:02:14.536
In the Romantic music that we
have been listening to,

00:02:14.536 --> 00:02:18.507
we would hear these long,
somewhat amorphous melodies,

00:02:18.507 --> 00:02:21.280
amorphous in terms of the
rhythm.

00:02:21.280 --> 00:02:25.598
But now here with the advent of
Modernism in the twentieth

00:02:25.598 --> 00:02:29.538
century we get a much more
driving type of rhythm.

00:02:29.538 --> 00:02:32.601
It almost in some ways goes
back to the driving rhythms of

00:02:32.601 --> 00:02:35.180
the Baroque except with one
major difference,

00:02:35.180 --> 00:02:37.830
and that is that these modern
rhythms are highly irregular.

00:02:37.830 --> 00:02:42.740
What we get oftentimes are
irregular meters.

00:02:42.740 --> 00:02:45.240
What would you imagine an
irregular meter is?

00:02:45.240 --> 00:02:49.050
Anyone want to field that one,
irregular meters?

00:02:49.050 --> 00:02:52.036
Well, simply said,
it's not a succession of

00:02:52.036 --> 00:02:53.637
two-four,
two-four, two-four,

00:02:53.637 --> 00:02:56.146
two-four or three-four,
three-four, but two-four,

00:02:56.146 --> 00:02:58.123
five-four,
four-four, two-four,

00:02:58.123 --> 00:03:00.240
six-four, three-eight,
and so on.

00:03:00.240 --> 00:03:03.348
Each measure can have a
different meter.

00:03:03.348 --> 00:03:05.252
In addition,
we also have this phenomenon

00:03:05.252 --> 00:03:08.201
called polymeters in which you
could assign to your clarinet to

00:03:08.201 --> 00:03:11.199
play in three- four and your
bassoon to play in four-four,

00:03:11.199 --> 00:03:12.878
and maybe your violins in
seven-eight.

00:03:12.878 --> 00:03:16.465
So as a result,
you get something of a

00:03:16.465 --> 00:03:21.990
disjunctive, rhythmic texture
here, disjointed rhythms.

00:03:21.990 --> 00:03:26.798
And the second aspect of this
approach to Modernism has

00:03:26.798 --> 00:03:30.449
something to do with the
orchestration.

00:03:30.449 --> 00:03:34.279
There's a great deal more
emphasis now on percussive

00:03:34.279 --> 00:03:35.030
effects.
 

00:03:35.030 --> 00:03:38.549
New instruments are added to
the orchestra,

00:03:38.549 --> 00:03:42.739
instruments called the
xylophone, the glockenspiel,

00:03:42.739 --> 00:03:44.080
the celesta.
 

00:03:44.080 --> 00:03:46.651
And if you want to see a
picture of some of these you

00:03:46.651 --> 00:03:48.729
could open your textbook at some
point--

00:03:48.729 --> 00:03:51.508
just write this in your
notes--see figure--

00:03:51.508 --> 00:03:54.370
I think I wrote it down
here--figure ten--

00:03:54.370 --> 00:03:57.224
no, excuse me--five,
number ten, chapter five,

00:03:57.224 --> 00:03:58.050
number ten.
 

00:03:58.050 --> 00:03:59.598
You can see some of these
percussion instruments,

00:03:59.598 --> 00:04:03.343
but basically they're just
either sticks or pieces of metal

00:04:03.343 --> 00:04:08.247
bars that you beat with sticks,
or, in the case of the celesta,

00:04:08.247 --> 00:04:10.870
you activate with a keyboard.
 

00:04:10.870 --> 00:04:14.670
So we've got these two things
here: driving but irregular

00:04:14.670 --> 00:04:18.879
rhythms and we also have this
new approach to orchestration.

00:04:18.879 --> 00:04:23.317
So let's listen to a bit now of
Igor Stravinsky's ballet of

00:04:23.317 --> 00:04:25.230
1911, Petrushka.
 

00:04:25.230 --> 00:04:34.360
&gt;
 

00:04:34.360 --> 00:04:36.579
Can you conduct this?
 

00:04:36.579 --> 00:04:59.199
&gt;
 

00:04:59.199 --> 00:05:01.600
Jacob and I were fooling around
with this in the background,

00:05:01.600 --> 00:05:03.500
trying to figure out what these
meters were,

00:05:03.500 --> 00:05:05.680
see if we could pick up these
different changes,

00:05:05.680 --> 00:05:09.050
but they are as--and how'd we
do?

00:05:09.050 --> 00:05:10.069
Not well.
 

00:05:10.069 --> 00:05:11.639
Jacob says we did not do well.
 

00:05:11.639 --> 00:05:14.855
Because without the score,
it's difficult to anticipate

00:05:14.855 --> 00:05:17.000
which meter is going to come
next.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:20.480
And you heard the intense
percussive effects there.

00:05:20.480 --> 00:05:24.084
But Stravinsky's most radical
statement of Modernism occurs

00:05:24.084 --> 00:05:26.074
not here in
"Petrushka"

00:05:26.074 --> 00:05:29.370
but two years later in The
Rite of Spring.

00:05:29.370 --> 00:05:35.036
It premiered in Paris in May of
1913, and it's become something

00:05:35.036 --> 00:05:39.514
of a cultural icon,
this whole idea of the Rite

00:05:39.514 --> 00:05:41.160
of Spring.
 

00:05:41.160 --> 00:05:44.535
Indeed I have this book,
and I've had it for quite a

00:05:44.535 --> 00:05:47.910
while, Rites of Spring by
Modris Eksteins.

00:05:47.910 --> 00:05:51.045
It's often required reading in
the history department here,

00:05:51.045 --> 00:05:52.019
history program.
 

00:05:52.019 --> 00:05:54.869
Has anybody ever run into this,
been asked to read anything by

00:05:54.869 --> 00:05:55.709
Modris Eksteins?
 

00:05:55.709 --> 00:05:59.245
Well, the subtitle is here:
The Great War and the Birth

00:05:59.245 --> 00:06:02.437
of the Modern Age,
but it's not accidental

00:06:02.437 --> 00:06:06.281
that he is playing off of this
title of a ballet of Igor

00:06:06.281 --> 00:06:08.651
Stravinsky,
because the ballet of

00:06:08.651 --> 00:06:10.980
Stravinsky was a kind of
watershed,

00:06:10.980 --> 00:06:14.569
a touchstone,
the benchmark from which

00:06:14.569 --> 00:06:19.807
Modernism can be calculated and
against which it can be

00:06:19.807 --> 00:06:21.069
measured.
 

00:06:21.069 --> 00:06:24.625
So when the audience arrived
there at the Theatre

00:06:24.625 --> 00:06:29.019
Champs-Elysees in Paris--and
that theatre still is there.

00:06:29.019 --> 00:06:32.940
You can walk down the Avenue
Montagne--it's where Hermes is

00:06:32.940 --> 00:06:35.779
and Gucci and all of these fancy
stores;

00:06:35.779 --> 00:06:38.649
it's there in Paris--and go in
and still hear concerts there.

00:06:38.649 --> 00:06:41.016
I've heard concerts in the
Theatre Champs-Elysees so

00:06:41.016 --> 00:06:42.240
you can still do that today.
 

00:06:42.240 --> 00:06:43.202
It's still functioning.
 

00:06:43.202 --> 00:06:45.129
It's one of the major concert
halls in Paris.

00:06:45.129 --> 00:06:49.389
So, in any event,
May 1913, the audience arrives.

00:06:49.389 --> 00:06:51.940
They are there to hear a
Russian ballet.

00:06:51.940 --> 00:06:54.170
What kind of music do they
expect to hear?

00:06:54.170 --> 00:06:57.009
Well, let's listen to what they
were expecting to hear.

00:06:57.009 --> 00:07:03.160
&gt;
 

00:07:03.160 --> 00:07:05.350
So whose music is this?
 

00:07:05.350 --> 00:07:06.040
Student: Tchaikovsky.
 

00:07:06.040 --> 00:07:07.319
Prof: Tchaikovsky.
 

00:07:07.319 --> 00:07:10.740
Anybody--Leah,
you know the title of it?

00:07:10.740 --> 00:07:13.946
"Swan Lake,"
so lots of tutus and pas de

00:07:13.946 --> 00:07:16.290
deux up there and moving
around.

00:07:16.290 --> 00:07:20.600
So this is what they thought
Russian ballet was.

00:07:20.600 --> 00:07:26.879
So they arrive and take their
seats.

00:07:26.879 --> 00:07:28.569
The lights go down.
 

00:07:28.569 --> 00:07:32.956
Everybody is properly dressed
for this particular occasion and

00:07:32.956 --> 00:07:36.050
here is the kind of music that
they hear.

00:07:36.050 --> 00:07:57.790
&gt;
 

00:07:57.790 --> 00:08:02.009
So that's a radically new
sound, a radically new approach

00:08:02.009 --> 00:08:04.490
to modern art,
and indeed, once again,

00:08:04.490 --> 00:08:06.697
if you ask,
generally, cultural historians

00:08:06.697 --> 00:08:09.398
to put their finger on the
moment that constitutes the

00:08:09.398 --> 00:08:12.505
beginning of Modernism it would
probably be this moment of the

00:08:12.505 --> 00:08:14.850
performance of The Rite of
Spring.

00:08:14.850 --> 00:08:18.689
How did Stravinsky create these
radically new sounds?

00:08:18.689 --> 00:08:21.139
Well, he did so in a couple of
ways.

00:08:21.139 --> 00:08:28.420
We've been talking before about
this idea of irregular meters.

00:08:28.420 --> 00:08:30.410
Let's see how these play out.
 

00:08:30.410 --> 00:08:32.120
The music that you were just
listening to--

00:08:32.120 --> 00:08:35.879
not the pitches but the
durations--are up here on the

00:08:35.879 --> 00:08:37.395
board,
and they're all,

00:08:37.395 --> 00:08:39.129
as you can see,
quarter notes,

00:08:39.129 --> 00:08:41.539
but they are grouped in
different sorts of ways,

00:08:41.539 --> 00:08:42.928
grouped by these accents.
 

00:08:42.928 --> 00:08:46.788
So I've asked Jacob--Jacob's up
here--to grab his viola now.

00:08:46.788 --> 00:08:49.903
He's going to come over and
play the sequence for us

00:08:49.903 --> 00:08:53.017
following the accents,
and then he will be joined by

00:08:53.017 --> 00:08:54.299
our guest artist.
 

00:08:54.299 --> 00:09:00.740
 
 

00:09:00.740 --> 00:09:08.909
&gt;
 

00:09:08.909 --> 00:09:12.178
Okay. So that's the way it goes.
 

00:09:12.178 --> 00:09:14.701
That's all the violin--or the
violist or violinist,

00:09:14.701 --> 00:09:15.759
all the strings do.
 

00:09:15.759 --> 00:09:17.788
Let's do that one more time
with our guest artist.

00:09:17.788 --> 00:09:20.210
We're going to add percussion
now.

00:09:20.210 --> 00:09:36.990
&gt;
 

00:09:36.990 --> 00:09:38.629
Ah, what a virtuoso duo.
 

00:09:38.629 --> 00:09:40.200
&gt;
 

00:09:40.200 --> 00:09:44.320
Okay.
 

00:09:44.320 --> 00:09:48.980
So that was--Jacob,
don't go away completely here.

00:09:48.980 --> 00:09:51.857
One other point:
watch Jacob's hand when he is

00:09:51.857 --> 00:09:52.690
doing this.
 

00:09:52.690 --> 00:09:55.070
This is not the way string
players normally play.

00:09:55.070 --> 00:09:59.453
He's doing something
extraordinary here and it tells

00:09:59.453 --> 00:10:03.150
us--we don't hear--when you play
Tchaikovsky

00:10:03.150 --> 00:10:04.956
&gt;
 

00:10:04.956 --> 00:10:08.740
, but that ain't what he's
playing now.

00:10:08.740 --> 00:10:13.460
&gt;
 

00:10:13.460 --> 00:10:15.490
Okay. So what's he doing?
 

00:10:15.490 --> 00:10:17.720
He's playing all with--
Student: Down bows.

00:10:17.720 --> 00:10:21.354
Prof: Down bows,
everything down bow,

00:10:21.354 --> 00:10:26.509
and that's counterintuitive to
your normal string teaching.

00:10:26.509 --> 00:10:29.509
So we've taken these string
instruments and instead of using

00:10:29.509 --> 00:10:32.846
them as these warm,
vibrato-filled communicators

00:10:32.846 --> 00:10:35.267
we're--
in the string family we're sort

00:10:35.267 --> 00:10:38.149
of turning them in now to
percussion instruments.

00:10:38.149 --> 00:10:39.379
That's a very percussive effect.
 

00:10:39.379 --> 00:10:43.158
So not only do we have new
percussion instruments;

00:10:43.158 --> 00:10:47.360
we have percussive effects with
the existing instruments.

00:10:47.360 --> 00:10:50.996
And perhaps most important here
is the chord,

00:10:50.996 --> 00:10:55.129
the music that Stravinsky is
setting forth here.

00:10:55.129 --> 00:10:57.059
It's an odd chord.
 

00:10:57.059 --> 00:10:58.600
It's an odd occurrence.
 

00:10:58.600 --> 00:11:02.486
What he's got here is a
perfectly innocuous E major

00:11:02.486 --> 00:11:03.110
triad.
 

00:11:03.110 --> 00:11:04.419
&gt;
 

00:11:04.419 --> 00:11:06.039
I'll put it down here an octave.
 

00:11:06.039 --> 00:11:07.509
&gt;
 

00:11:07.509 --> 00:11:10.524
And then on top of it he's got
a seventh chord starting on

00:11:10.524 --> 00:11:11.000
E-flat.
 

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.250
&gt;
 

00:11:13.250 --> 00:11:17.320
And either--each of those--each
&gt;

00:11:17.320 --> 00:11:22.009
by itself is rather consonant,
but you put the two of them

00:11:22.009 --> 00:11:25.220
together &lt;&lt;plays
piano&gt;&gt;.

00:11:25.220 --> 00:11:28.405
So this is a good example of
another way that Modernism in

00:11:28.405 --> 00:11:30.809
music is created,
and that's for the use of,

00:11:30.809 --> 00:11:32.600
very obviously,
a polychord.

00:11:32.600 --> 00:11:34.690
Interesting point.
 

00:11:34.690 --> 00:11:38.379
I'm going to go to some slides
now because it's exactly at this

00:11:38.379 --> 00:11:42.128
time in the history of art that
painters started doing this same

00:11:42.128 --> 00:11:43.200
kind of thing.
 

00:11:43.200 --> 00:11:45.019
So we're going to go to the
first slide here.

00:11:45.019 --> 00:11:46.288
Who painted this, please?
 

00:11:46.288 --> 00:11:47.548
Student:
&gt;

00:11:47.548 --> 00:11:49.654
Prof: Nice and loud.
 

00:11:49.654 --> 00:11:51.450
I hear it in the back.
 

00:11:51.450 --> 00:11:51.960
Student: Picasso.
 

00:11:51.960 --> 00:11:52.730
Prof: Picasso. Okay.
 

00:11:52.730 --> 00:11:54.950
"Three Musicians"
by Pablo Picasso.

00:11:54.950 --> 00:11:59.559
And what we have here is sort
of one musician kind of out of

00:11:59.559 --> 00:12:03.174
phase with himself--
one musician and then another

00:12:03.174 --> 00:12:06.899
musician slightly in an
irregular position against that.

00:12:06.899 --> 00:12:11.450
Next type of slide here:
This is Georges Braque,

00:12:11.450 --> 00:12:16.173
"Woman with Violin,"
a little bit difficult to see

00:12:16.173 --> 00:12:20.578
the woman there in the context
of this highly fragmented

00:12:20.578 --> 00:12:21.460
violin.
 

00:12:21.460 --> 00:12:25.879
Now we're going to go on to
Juan Gris' "Violin"

00:12:25.879 --> 00:12:30.301
and now we're going to go on to
a slide taken from a book

00:12:30.301 --> 00:12:33.379
published in 1916by Albert
Gleizes.

00:12:33.379 --> 00:12:44.139
 
 

00:12:44.139 --> 00:12:47.480
But we can see the point here.
 

00:12:47.480 --> 00:12:50.178
Off to the left we have just a
square.

00:12:50.178 --> 00:12:53.210
And that square then is being
rotated against itself.

00:12:53.210 --> 00:12:55.440
It's being rotated
itself--against itself in

00:12:55.440 --> 00:12:57.826
another position,
rotated itself in yet another

00:12:57.826 --> 00:13:00.678
position, and that's all these
musicians are doing.

00:13:00.678 --> 00:13:03.910
They're taking one triad and
then taking the triad right next

00:13:03.910 --> 00:13:07.250
to each other so the triads are
slightly out of phase with each

00:13:07.250 --> 00:13:07.788
other.
 

00:13:07.788 --> 00:13:12.070
And ultimately it produces a
rather dissonant configuration.

00:13:12.070 --> 00:13:13.405
Okay.
 

00:13:13.405 --> 00:13:25.700
That's all we need here by way
of the slides.

00:13:25.700 --> 00:13:29.157
Well, the premiere of The
Rite of Spring was just as

00:13:29.157 --> 00:13:31.720
dissonant as some of these
paintings are.

00:13:31.720 --> 00:13:33.750
Indeed, it caused a scandal.
 

00:13:33.750 --> 00:13:35.038
It caused a riot.
 

00:13:35.038 --> 00:13:39.019
It created the most infamous--I
guess--

00:13:39.019 --> 00:13:44.080
riot in the history of music,
and we have,

00:13:44.080 --> 00:13:46.961
fortunately,
and they are contained here in

00:13:46.961 --> 00:13:50.048
Modris Eksteins's book among
other places,

00:13:50.048 --> 00:13:52.715
some primary source
accounts--people who were there

00:13:52.715 --> 00:13:56.019
at the time telling what it was
like to be at this premiere.

00:13:56.019 --> 00:13:57.928
So here are a couple of direct
quotes.

00:13:57.928 --> 00:14:02.044
"Then ensued a battery of
screams countered by a foil of

00:14:02.044 --> 00:14:02.799
applause.
 

00:14:02.799 --> 00:14:04.918
We warred over art."
 

00:14:04.918 --> 00:14:07.000
I like that:
"warred over art."

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:10.120
"Or what some thought was
art but others didn't.

00:14:10.120 --> 00:14:13.458
About forty of the protesters
were forced out of the theater

00:14:13.458 --> 00:14:15.724
by the police,
but that did not quell the

00:14:15.724 --> 00:14:16.629
disturbance.
 

00:14:16.629 --> 00:14:19.711
The lights in the auditorium
were turned fully on,

00:14:19.711 --> 00:14:23.232
but that did not still the
disjointed ravings of a mob of

00:14:23.232 --> 00:14:25.120
angry men and women."
 

00:14:25.120 --> 00:14:26.125
End quote.
 

00:14:26.125 --> 00:14:29.450
And here's another direct
quote.

00:14:29.450 --> 00:14:32.580
"I was sitting in a box in
which I had rented one seat.

00:14:32.580 --> 00:14:35.467
Three ladies sat in front of me
and a young man occupied the

00:14:35.467 --> 00:14:36.350
place behind me.
 

00:14:36.350 --> 00:14:39.698
He stood up during the course
of the ballet to see more

00:14:39.698 --> 00:14:40.320
clearly.
 

00:14:40.320 --> 00:14:43.259
The intense excitement under
which he was laboring,

00:14:43.259 --> 00:14:45.288
thanks to the potent force of
the music,

00:14:45.288 --> 00:14:50.129
portrayed itself presently when
he began to beat rhythmically

00:14:50.129 --> 00:14:53.759
with his fists on the top of my
head."

00:14:53.759 --> 00:14:54.621
&gt;
 

00:14:54.621 --> 00:14:55.450
&gt;
 

00:14:55.450 --> 00:14:56.788
End quote.
 

00:14:56.788 --> 00:14:59.851
Well, what is it,
again, specifically in this

00:14:59.851 --> 00:15:03.750
music of Stravinsky that causes
this kind of reaction?

00:15:03.750 --> 00:15:07.720
Let me list for you--let me
enumerate five things here.

00:15:07.720 --> 00:15:09.500
One: heavy dissonance.
 

00:15:09.500 --> 00:15:12.259
We just heard some of that,
&gt;

00:15:12.259 --> 00:15:14.519
that kind of sound,
almost a cluster-type

00:15:14.519 --> 00:15:17.299
dissonance,
heavy dissonance created by

00:15:17.299 --> 00:15:21.650
polychords in which we have
triads and these triads are only

00:15:21.650 --> 00:15:23.200
a half step apart.
 

00:15:23.200 --> 00:15:24.870
The roots are only a half step
apart.

00:15:24.870 --> 00:15:26.250
So one: heavy dissonance.
 

00:15:26.250 --> 00:15:29.447
Two: much greater reliance on
percussion: tympani,

00:15:29.447 --> 00:15:32.320
glockenspiel,
celesta, that sort of thing.

00:15:32.320 --> 00:15:36.583
Three: as we saw with Jacob,
the use of stringed instruments

00:15:36.583 --> 00:15:40.346
as percussion instruments,
so a new use of these

00:15:40.346 --> 00:15:43.628
traditional instruments,
and even the piano,

00:15:43.628 --> 00:15:45.360
this banging on the piano.
 

00:15:45.360 --> 00:15:48.360
The percussion--the piano is
technically a percussion

00:15:48.360 --> 00:15:51.190
instrument but it's a
particularly lyrical one.

00:15:51.190 --> 00:15:54.820
Well, it's not so lyrically
used here in the modern idiom.

00:15:54.820 --> 00:15:58.519
Number four:
an increased use of woodwinds.

00:15:58.519 --> 00:16:00.678
The strings fall into the
background.

00:16:00.678 --> 00:16:03.802
The woodwinds with their
potentially bright,

00:16:03.802 --> 00:16:06.490
brittle sound are now
foregrounded.

00:16:06.490 --> 00:16:11.158
And fifth: this idea of rhythm,
driving rhythms,

00:16:11.158 --> 00:16:16.791
yes, but irregular rhythms and
polymeters and irregular meters

00:16:16.791 --> 00:16:21.129
all creating this kind of
disjunctive effect.

00:16:21.129 --> 00:16:24.128
So let's listen now to a
passage out of Stravinsky's

00:16:24.128 --> 00:16:25.539
Rite of Spring.
 

00:16:25.539 --> 00:16:26.240
You heard one of them.
 

00:16:26.240 --> 00:16:30.993
Let's listen to another one in
which all five of these elements

00:16:30.993 --> 00:16:32.220
sound at once.
 

00:16:32.220 --> 00:17:14.279
&gt;
 

00:17:14.279 --> 00:17:15.930
