00:18:00.250 --> 00:18:02.765
You've got to really get used
to it over the years,

00:18:02.765 --> 00:18:05.078
mushrooms or whatever it might
happen to be.

00:18:05.078 --> 00:18:07.923
I first heard this piece in
nineteen sixty-seven,

00:18:07.923 --> 00:18:08.990
when I was a TA.
 

00:18:08.990 --> 00:18:11.923
I had to teach it and I didn't
really know it,

00:18:11.923 --> 00:18:15.835
and then I had the honor and
pleasure of hearing it performed

00:18:15.835 --> 00:18:17.528
live in Paris in 1970.
 

00:18:17.528 --> 00:18:20.999
And it was really an epiphany
because I was sitting there--I

00:18:20.999 --> 00:18:22.470
remember it distinctly.
 

00:18:22.470 --> 00:18:24.832
It was in a boxing arena,
of all places,

00:18:24.832 --> 00:18:28.346
but they had an elevated stage
and the dancers came out and

00:18:28.346 --> 00:18:30.709
they started going
&gt;

00:18:30.709 --> 00:18:33.678
, that kind of thing,
and the whole arena began to

00:18:33.678 --> 00:18:35.920
shake and I said,
"Whoa.

00:18:35.920 --> 00:18:37.630
I now understand. I get it.
 

00:18:37.630 --> 00:18:39.108
It's not just the music.
 

00:18:39.108 --> 00:18:41.970
Music is just part of this
total artistic experience.

00:18:41.970 --> 00:18:45.835
It's a kind of sympathetic
vibration in conjunction with

00:18:45.835 --> 00:18:50.053
the kinetic experience of the
dance that really brings all of

00:18:50.053 --> 00:18:51.670
this to life."
 

00:18:51.670 --> 00:18:55.506
So music here is just a kind of
catalyst for the ballet and to

00:18:55.506 --> 00:18:58.838
really begin to appreciate
something such as this,

00:18:58.838 --> 00:19:00.808
Stravinsky's approach to
Modernism,

00:19:00.808 --> 00:19:04.508
we've kind of--we do,
in fact--have to see it to

00:19:04.508 --> 00:19:06.240
