00:21:35.858 --> 00:21:39.282
So I'm going to go back to one
of my favorite composers and

00:21:39.282 --> 00:21:40.700
that is Gustav Mahler.
 

00:21:40.700 --> 00:21:44.435
We talked a little bit about
Gustav Mahler when we had our

00:21:44.435 --> 00:21:47.910
lecture on the symphony in the
nineteenth century,

00:21:47.910 --> 00:21:52.019
and we said that Mahler was of
Jewish descent,

00:21:52.019 --> 00:21:55.150
from what is now a portion of
the Czech Republic,

00:21:55.150 --> 00:21:57.660
who came in to Vienna to study
music.

00:21:57.660 --> 00:22:00.202
He started as a pianist,
became a conductor,

00:22:00.202 --> 00:22:03.278
and basically he earned his
living as a conductor.

00:22:03.278 --> 00:22:06.644
He got small-time jobs out in
the provinces and then

00:22:06.644 --> 00:22:09.548
ultimately worked his way back
to Vienna,

00:22:09.548 --> 00:22:13.190
where he became the conductor
of the Staatsoper in

00:22:13.190 --> 00:22:14.805
Vienna,
and if you ever go to

00:22:14.805 --> 00:22:16.690
Vienna--and you should all go to
Vienna.

00:22:16.690 --> 00:22:18.509
It's an incredibly musical city.
 

00:22:18.509 --> 00:22:21.490
Everywhere you go you see these
silhouettes of Mozart.

00:22:21.490 --> 00:22:22.788
It is so cool.
 

00:22:22.788 --> 00:22:26.182
So you have to go to--you can't
walk a block without seeing

00:22:26.182 --> 00:22:26.710
Mozart.
 

00:22:26.710 --> 00:22:27.900
It's to die for.
 

00:22:27.900 --> 00:22:30.614
So there we are on the
Ringstrasse with the

00:22:30.614 --> 00:22:34.125
great Staatsoper,
and this is where Gustav Mahler

00:22:34.125 --> 00:22:38.065
conducted and it's still there,
but Mahler was a difficult

00:22:38.065 --> 00:22:39.858
person to get along with.
 

00:22:39.858 --> 00:22:43.190
I suppose oftentimes great
artists are, geniuses are.

00:22:43.190 --> 00:22:45.796
They tend to be
self-referential and maybe

00:22:45.796 --> 00:22:49.608
rightly so, but in any event,
he was an orchestral tyrant.

00:22:49.608 --> 00:22:52.473
His players didn't like playing
for them, and after ten years

00:22:52.473 --> 00:22:54.048
they didn't renew his contract.
 

00:22:54.048 --> 00:22:56.318
In effect, he was fired in
Vienna but,

00:22:56.318 --> 00:23:00.118
as good fortune had it,
he was able--

00:23:00.118 --> 00:23:03.246
or at that time there was an
opening in New York City so he

00:23:03.246 --> 00:23:06.480
comes to New York to conduct
first the Metropolitan Opera and

00:23:06.480 --> 00:23:09.715
then a year or so later he took
on what was to become the New

00:23:09.715 --> 00:23:11.009
York Philharmonic.
 

00:23:11.009 --> 00:23:13.336
So there he is,
the principal conductor,

00:23:13.336 --> 00:23:14.710
now in New York City.
 

00:23:14.710 --> 00:23:22.778
Interestingly enough,
on two occasions Mahler came to

00:23:22.778 --> 00:23:24.640
New Haven.
 

00:23:24.640 --> 00:23:26.098
He came to New Haven.
 

00:23:26.098 --> 00:23:30.874
He brought--first was in 1910,
he brought the New York

00:23:30.874 --> 00:23:35.828
Philharmonic to New Haven and
where did they perform?

00:23:35.828 --> 00:23:39.880
Where would you imagine they'd
perform?

00:23:39.880 --> 00:23:42.559
Woolsey Hall. Okay?
 

00:23:42.559 --> 00:23:43.788
Woolsey Hall.
 

00:23:43.788 --> 00:23:47.150
Woolsey Hall was built for
Gustav Mahler.

00:23:47.150 --> 00:23:47.384
No.
 

00:23:47.384 --> 00:23:51.307
That's not really true,
but it gets across a point:

00:23:51.307 --> 00:23:55.699
that Woolsey Hall was built to
be a concert hall for what

00:23:55.699 --> 00:24:00.011
Gustav Mahler represented,
which was the apotheosis,

00:24:00.011 --> 00:24:02.917
the ultimate flourishing,
although they didn't know it

00:24:02.917 --> 00:24:05.614
was the ultimate at the time,
of this great instrument,

00:24:05.614 --> 00:24:08.490
which was the
nineteenth-century orchestra.

00:24:08.490 --> 00:24:12.288
So Mahler brings the New York
Philharmonic to Woolsey Hall.

00:24:12.288 --> 00:24:15.432
The next time you're in Woolsey
Hall, think of Gustav Mahler

00:24:15.432 --> 00:24:17.190
standing on those boards there.
 

