a streptococcal infection,
a lingering streptococcal

00:26:22.038 --> 00:26:25.715
infection in the area of the
heart that had greatly weakened

00:26:25.715 --> 00:26:29.269
his heart so the doctors at
Yale-New Haven Hospital--

00:26:29.269 --> 00:26:30.884
New Haven Hospital said,
"There's really nothing we

00:26:30.884 --> 00:26:31.558
can do for you."
 

00:26:31.558 --> 00:26:35.009
He goes back to New York,
goes immediately back to Vienna

00:26:35.009 --> 00:26:38.400
and he dies within six weeks of
this heart condition.

00:26:38.400 --> 00:26:41.375
And we have--and I'm delighted
to say Dr. James Hines has

00:26:41.375 --> 00:26:42.970
been with us all semester.
 

00:26:42.970 --> 00:26:46.349
Jim, thank you for your
attendance--a cardiologist.

00:26:46.349 --> 00:26:47.420
He has been here.
 

00:26:47.420 --> 00:26:49.554
You may have thought that this
was just accidental,

00:26:49.554 --> 00:26:51.390
but in case--I was thinking
this morning.

00:26:51.390 --> 00:26:54.205
We've never told you that we
had--if your heart begins to

00:26:54.205 --> 00:26:57.273
palpitate when you're listening
to all this really great music

00:26:57.273 --> 00:26:59.838
and you become aphasic or
something like that,

00:26:59.838 --> 00:27:02.748
we have an attendant here ready
to serve you in the form of

00:27:02.748 --> 00:27:03.450
Dr. Hines.
 

00:27:03.450 --> 00:27:06.352
So you've been in good hands
all along and thank you,

00:27:06.352 --> 00:27:07.578
Jim, for being here.
 

00:27:07.578 --> 00:27:13.597
So let's take a look at some of
the things that Gustav Mahler

00:27:13.597 --> 00:27:18.112
composed here,
and I think we've got a list up

00:27:18.112 --> 00:27:19.415
on the board.
 

00:27:19.415 --> 00:27:20.420
Okay.
 

00:27:20.420 --> 00:27:22.519
Symphonies: nine symphonies.
 

00:27:22.519 --> 00:27:25.768
Why is it that everybody
composes nine symphonies and

00:27:25.768 --> 00:27:28.079
then they die--
&gt;

00:27:28.079 --> 00:27:29.079
--stop at eight.
 

00:27:29.079 --> 00:27:29.578
No.
 

00:27:29.578 --> 00:27:33.048
He composed also nine
symphonies.

00:27:33.048 --> 00:27:36.201
He composed nine symphonies and
if you like Mahler,

00:27:36.201 --> 00:27:39.856
and I hope you will come to
like Mahler, I think there's an

00:27:39.856 --> 00:27:42.190
entry path into these
symphonies.

00:27:42.190 --> 00:27:43.740
Start with number four.
 

00:27:43.740 --> 00:27:46.200
It's the most user friendly,
then number one.

00:27:46.200 --> 00:27:49.542
We played two tracks out of
number one in that symphony

00:27:49.542 --> 00:27:52.640
lecture so you know that it's a
great piece too.

00:27:52.640 --> 00:27:56.386
Then Symphony number five,
which is worth the price of

00:27:56.386 --> 00:27:59.851
admission, really,
if for no other reason than the

00:27:59.851 --> 00:28:01.690
middle movement there.
 

00:28:01.690 --> 00:28:04.630
That Adagietto is just
so heartbreakingly beautiful

00:28:04.630 --> 00:28:06.538
that no one would want to miss
it,

00:28:06.538 --> 00:28:09.940
and then ultimately a little
bit more challenging symphonies,

00:28:09.940 --> 00:28:12.910
bigger symphonies:
number eight and number nine.

00:28:12.910 --> 00:28:16.500
Mahler also wrote,
as you can see up there,

00:28:16.500 --> 00:28:18.808
two collections of songs.
 

00:28:18.808 --> 00:28:22.890
They're called orchestral
Lieder.

00:28:22.890 --> 00:28:25.450
We have this orchestral Lied.
 

00:28:25.450 --> 00:28:28.380
It simply means orchestral song.
 

00:28:28.380 --> 00:28:32.220
We've had the Lied before in
our course.

00:28:32.220 --> 00:28:33.960
Where?
 

00:28:33.960 --> 00:28:37.818
Indeed, what was the name of
the Lied that we worked with?

00:28:37.818 --> 00:28:45.049
Composer's name,
the name of the piece?

00:28:45.049 --> 00:28:47.740
Hm?
 

00:28:47.740 --> 00:28:52.210
Student:
&gt;

00:28:52.210 --> 00:28:54.599
Prof: Okay. That's it.
 

00:28:54.599 --> 00:28:55.828
What was the name of the piece?
 

00:28:55.828 --> 00:28:56.788
Student:
&gt;

00:28:56.788 --> 00:28:57.662
Prof: "The Elf
King." Thank you,

00:28:57.662 --> 00:28:57.880
Frederick.
 

00:28:57.880 --> 00:28:59.470
And who was the composer?
 

00:28:59.470 --> 00:29:00.400
Student:
&gt;

00:29:00.400 --> 00:29:01.997
Prof: Franz Schubert.
 

00:29:01.997 --> 00:29:02.338
Okay.
 

00:29:02.338 --> 00:29:05.898
So we've had a--that's a Lied
for piano but now we have a Lied

00:29:05.898 --> 00:29:08.932
for voice and orchestra,
so it tends to be bigger and

00:29:08.932 --> 00:29:10.099
more flamboyant.
 

00:29:10.099 --> 00:29:11.298
This is a new genre.
 

00:29:11.298 --> 00:29:14.652
It's longer,
it's more colorful,

00:29:14.652 --> 00:29:20.598
yet it features a single voice
singing a single text.

00:29:20.598 --> 00:29:24.494
So we're going to focus
on--now--on one of Gustav

00:29:24.494 --> 00:29:28.876
Mahler's orchestral Lieds,
and it's talked about in the

00:29:28.876 --> 00:29:32.608
textbook there right before
Impressionism.

00:29:32.608 --> 00:29:34.779
No Listening Exercise on it
and, as I say,

00:29:34.779 --> 00:29:38.477
it's in there just because I
think it's a drop-dead beautiful

00:29:38.477 --> 00:29:42.050
piece and I want to try to
proselytize a bit with regard to

00:29:42.050 --> 00:29:44.269
Mahler's music so it has a text.
 

00:29:44.269 --> 00:29:45.220
Here's the text.
 

00:29:45.220 --> 00:29:48.710
The text is by romantic German
poet Friedrich Ruckert.

00:29:48.710 --> 00:29:54.664
We're now talking about
"Ich bin der Welt abhanden

00:29:54.664 --> 00:29:59.517
gekommen"
by Friedrich Ruckert as set in

00:29:59.517 --> 00:30:04.480
this collection of five songs
about 1902.

00:30:04.480 --> 00:30:07.578
And let's take a look at the
German here just for a moment,

00:30:07.578 --> 00:30:09.875
"Ich bin der Welt abhanden
gekommen,"

00:30:09.875 --> 00:30:12.368
"I've become detached from
the world."

00:30:12.368 --> 00:30:16.660
And I thought it'd be nice to
hear a German speaker,

00:30:16.660 --> 00:30:19.009
or somebody that speaks pretty
good German,

00:30:19.009 --> 00:30:21.740
tackle this text so I've asked
a student,

00:30:21.740 --> 00:30:25.118
David Narotsky to stand up,
if you would.

00:30:25.118 --> 00:30:27.876
David's applying to med school.
 

00:30:27.876 --> 00:30:28.500
Right?
 

00:30:28.500 --> 00:30:30.990
You're going around for all
kinds of med school interviews

00:30:30.990 --> 00:30:33.700
but here he's putting on his
German hat for us this morning.

00:30:33.700 --> 00:30:36.328
So read the first strophe,
please, David.

00:30:36.328 --> 00:30:46.200
Student: &lt;&lt;speaks
German&gt;&gt;

00:30:46.200 --> 00:30:47.284
Prof: Okay.
 

00:30:47.284 --> 00:30:50.839
Let's cut to the last one and a
little bit more slowly and a

00:30:50.839 --> 00:30:52.828
little--because it slows down.
 

00:30:52.828 --> 00:30:54.940
So let's read it a little more
slowly.

00:30:54.940 --> 00:31:06.410
Student: &lt;&lt;speaks
German&gt;&gt;

00:31:06.410 --> 00:31:07.166
Prof: Okay.
 

00:31:07.166 --> 00:31:07.420
Great.
 

00:31:07.420 --> 00:31:08.220
Thanks very much.
 

00:31:08.220 --> 00:31:11.170
So, as you can see here,
this is, in a sense,

00:31:11.170 --> 00:31:16.185
old person's music in that this
is an individual that has become

00:31:16.185 --> 00:31:20.067
disenchanted--
is exhausted from the trials

00:31:20.067 --> 00:31:23.048
and tribulations of this world.
 

00:31:23.048 --> 00:31:25.614
There's that sense of "Ich
bin der Welt abhanden

00:31:25.614 --> 00:31:27.784
gekommen,"
I've become detached from the

00:31:27.784 --> 00:31:30.692
world and if you don't see much
of me anymore I don't really

00:31:30.692 --> 00:31:33.827
care because,
as it says in the last strophe,

00:31:33.827 --> 00:31:37.363
"Ich bin gestorben dem
Weltgetümmel,"

00:31:37.363 --> 00:31:40.690
I'm dead to the tumult I guess
of the world,

00:31:40.690 --> 00:31:43.256
"und ruh' in einem stillen
Gebiet,"

00:31:43.256 --> 00:31:47.164
and I rest now in a still land,
"ich leb' allein,"

00:31:47.164 --> 00:31:49.573
I'm living alone in my
heaven,"

00:31:49.573 --> 00:31:52.859
"in meinem Lieben,
in meinem Lied,"

00:31:52.859 --> 00:31:56.809
and there it's an interesting
play of the word Lied because

00:31:56.809 --> 00:31:58.650
it's not so much a song.
 

00:31:58.650 --> 00:32:02.625
This is a metaphor for all of
his music so this is an

00:32:02.625 --> 00:32:06.675
individual that has become
detached from the world and

00:32:06.675 --> 00:32:10.269
simply wants to live in the
world of music.

00:32:10.269 --> 00:32:12.220
So let's listen to a bit of it
now.

00:32:12.220 --> 00:32:18.608
And it starts out with an
English horn.

00:32:18.608 --> 00:32:21.162
Somebody tell us,
review for us,

00:32:21.162 --> 00:32:25.195
what an English horn is--talked
about this before.

00:32:25.195 --> 00:32:26.019
Jerry.
 

00:32:26.019 --> 00:32:28.230
Student:
&gt;

00:32:28.230 --> 00:32:29.858
Prof: A lower oboe.
 

00:32:29.858 --> 00:32:31.050
That's right,
a lower oboe,

00:32:31.050 --> 00:32:32.838
and it sounds a little bit
mournful,

00:32:32.838 --> 00:32:35.098
sounds a little bit nostalgic
here,

00:32:35.098 --> 00:32:38.667
so we hear a lovely harp
underneath and then the English

00:32:38.667 --> 00:32:42.625
horn will start with just one
phrase and then that phrase will

00:32:42.625 --> 00:32:43.210
grow.
 

00:32:43.210 --> 00:32:46.211
It's kind of a cell or a motive
growing into a longer melody as

00:32:46.211 --> 00:32:48.440
we discussed in the beginning of
the course.

00:32:48.440 --> 00:33:53.588
 
 

00:33:53.588 --> 00:33:56.758
It's an interesting song in
that--I'm going to vamp here

00:33:56.758 --> 00:33:57.910
just for a moment.
 

00:33:57.910 --> 00:34:01.627
It starts out with the harp
underneath and the English horn,

00:34:01.627 --> 00:34:05.410
and it's a movement in which
there is no brass whatsoever.

00:34:05.410 --> 00:34:08.110
So I believe we have it set up
now.

00:34:08.110 --> 00:34:10.735
It's not to be an exciting
movement, much more of a

00:34:10.735 --> 00:34:11.889
reflective movement.
 

00:34:11.889 --> 00:34:47.969
&gt;
 

00:34:47.969 --> 00:34:59.090
Passes off the melody to a
clarinet &lt;&lt;music

00:34:59.090 --> 00:35:03.030
playing&gt;&gt;
 

00:35:03.030 --> 00:35:05.349
and then the voice will come in.
 

00:35:05.349 --> 00:35:16.699
&gt;
 

00:35:16.699 --> 00:35:16.949
Okay.
 

00:35:16.949 --> 00:35:18.500
We're going to pause it there.
 

00:35:18.500 --> 00:35:23.309
Then we will go on to a little
bit of material from the climax

00:35:23.309 --> 00:35:26.780
of the song just by way of a
preview here.

00:35:26.780 --> 00:35:29.650
We're going to go on now to
4'47",

00:35:29.650 --> 00:35:33.567
if you will,
where he works up to a peak on

00:35:33.567 --> 00:35:36.398
this text,
"Ich leb' allein in meinem

00:35:36.398 --> 00:35:37.693
Himmel,
in meinem Lieben,

00:35:37.693 --> 00:35:38.760
in meinem Lied."
 

00:35:38.760 --> 00:36:33.170
&gt;
 

00:36:33.170 --> 00:36:43.010
A little bit of dissonance,
&gt;

00:36:43.010 --> 00:36:48.175
back to the tonic,
English horn comes back in,

00:36:48.175 --> 00:36:50.929
builds out the melody.
 

00:36:50.929 --> 00:37:12.119
&gt;
 

00:37:12.119 --> 00:37:12.380
Okay.
 

00:37:12.380 --> 00:37:15.351
Now we're going to pause it
here because there's one other

00:37:15.351 --> 00:37:18.164
small point that I want to make
and that has to do with

00:37:18.164 --> 00:37:19.989
a--what's called a suspension.
 

00:37:19.989 --> 00:37:24.166
A suspension is something that
composers set up in music to

00:37:24.166 --> 00:37:27.119
sort of make us feel a
particular way,

00:37:27.119 --> 00:37:30.697
and they'll start with this by
having a note be consonant

00:37:30.697 --> 00:37:32.550
&gt;
 

00:37:32.550 --> 00:37:34.806
and then having--moving the
harmony underneath of it

00:37:34.806 --> 00:37:36.090
&gt;
 

00:37:36.090 --> 00:37:39.268
to a dissonance and then
&gt;

00:37:39.268 --> 00:37:46.027
resolving it to a consonant
like that or maybe &lt;&lt;plays

00:37:46.027 --> 00:37:47.860
piano&gt;&gt;.
 

00:37:47.860 --> 00:37:51.550
And the longer they sit on the
dissonance, the more feeling,

00:37:51.550 --> 00:37:53.239
I think, is communicated.
 

00:37:53.239 --> 00:37:56.003
And here at the end of the
Romantic period it tends to

00:37:56.003 --> 00:37:58.820
be--they tend to sit on these
dissonances inside of the

00:37:58.820 --> 00:38:00.960
suspension for a long period of
time.

00:38:00.960 --> 00:38:05.007
So we're about to hear--We're
about to hear the strings go up

00:38:05.007 --> 00:38:08.922
and play a suspension and then
the English horn will do the

00:38:08.922 --> 00:38:09.530
same.
 

00:38:09.530 --> 00:38:20.119
There it is &lt;&lt;music
playing&gt;&gt;.

00:38:20.119 --> 00:38:27.786
Now the English horn will
suspend, &lt;&lt;music

00:38:27.786 --> 00:38:30.559
playing&gt;&gt;
 

00:38:30.559 --> 00:38:40.949
dissonance &lt;&lt;music
playing&gt;&gt;.

00:38:40.949 --> 00:38:43.159
Okay. So that's the piece.
 

00:38:43.159 --> 00:38:45.373
Now we're going to do something
we've only done on one other

00:38:45.373 --> 00:38:47.664
occasion in the class and that
is to listen to the whole piece

00:38:47.664 --> 00:38:48.639
from beginning to end.
 

00:38:48.639 --> 00:38:51.579
I'd like to do this and it may
be a little hokey I guess,

00:38:51.579 --> 00:38:52.840
but it doesn't matter.
 

00:38:52.840 --> 00:38:54.900
I'm going to turn off all the
lights here as best I can,

00:38:54.900 --> 00:38:57.989
and I do this because it gives
you a sense,

00:38:57.989 --> 00:39:01.250
sometimes, of what--at least
how I engage music oftentimes--

00:39:01.250 --> 00:39:03.309
what does it do for us?
 

00:39:03.309 --> 00:39:05.070
Well, we've talked before at
the beginning.

00:39:05.070 --> 00:39:08.340
It allows us to kind of relax,
center our attention.

00:39:08.340 --> 00:39:10.219
You're under a lot of stress at
the moment.

00:39:10.219 --> 00:39:13.800
This is the sort of climax,
crunch time,

00:39:13.800 --> 00:39:17.155
in the academic world so this
is an opportunity to kind of

00:39:17.155 --> 00:39:19.885
tune everything out,
maybe go inside of your own

00:39:19.885 --> 00:39:22.686
Gebiet here,
your own musical territory,

00:39:22.686 --> 00:39:25.780
and maybe think of things in
the past,

00:39:25.780 --> 00:39:28.956
music as a creator of
nostalgia, think of things that

00:39:28.956 --> 00:39:31.628
might be,
music giving us a vision

00:39:31.628 --> 00:39:35.378
perhaps of a better world,
whatever you'd like--whatever

00:39:35.378 --> 00:39:38.590
spin you want to put on this,
but we're going to be--each of

00:39:38.590 --> 00:39:41.780
us is now going to go into our
own zone here for about seven

00:39:41.780 --> 00:39:44.429
minutes as we listen to this
orchestral Lied,

00:39:44.429 --> 00:39:47.507
"Ich bin der Welt abhanden
gekommen,"

00:39:47.507 --> 00:39:48.780
by Gustav Mahler.
 

00:39:48.780 --> 00:46:43.579
&gt;
 

00:46:43.579 --> 00:46:43.840
Okay.
 

00:46:43.840 --> 00:46:46.711
So that's our last piece of
music for Listening to Music

00:46:46.711 --> 00:46:47.130
here.
 

00:46:47.130 --> 00:46:48.898
Now I'm going to tell you what
this class was really about.

00:46:48.898 --> 00:46:49.630
&gt;
 

00:46:49.630 --> 00:46:51.889
It wasn't about listening to
music.

00:46:51.889 --> 00:46:56.309
It was about saving classical
music.

00:46:56.309 --> 00:46:57.059
Why?
 

00:46:57.059 --> 00:46:59.510
Why would we want to save
classical music?

00:46:59.510 --> 00:47:02.050
We could spend hours discussing
that.

00:47:02.050 --> 00:47:06.835
We would want to save it,
arguably, because it is one of

00:47:06.835 --> 00:47:10.840
the things that we value in
Western culture.

00:47:10.840 --> 00:47:11.690
What do we value?
 

00:47:11.690 --> 00:47:12.840
I was thinking about this,
this morning.

00:47:12.840 --> 00:47:14.380
We've got--we just had a big
election.

00:47:14.380 --> 00:47:15.750
Right? We value democracy.
 

00:47:15.750 --> 00:47:18.389
We value religious freedom.
 

00:47:18.389 --> 00:47:22.050
We value equality of the sexes,
of gender.

00:47:22.050 --> 00:47:22.840
What else?
 

00:47:22.840 --> 00:47:24.519
Due process under the law.
 

00:47:24.519 --> 00:47:25.768
We value Shakespeare.
 

00:47:25.768 --> 00:47:29.644
We value Leonardo da Vinci and
the symphonies of Mozart for

00:47:29.644 --> 00:47:31.976
example,
and these are very important

00:47:31.976 --> 00:47:35.625
things and I think they're worth
fighting for and worth trying to

00:47:35.625 --> 00:47:36.309
preserve.
 

00:47:36.309 --> 00:47:39.329
Recently, somebody gave the
School of Music how much money?

00:47:39.329 --> 00:47:43.739
One hundred million dollars to
keep classical music alive.

00:47:43.739 --> 00:47:44.699
That's a lot of money.
 

00:47:44.699 --> 00:47:47.110
I've done my part,
showed up here every day,

00:47:47.110 --> 00:47:48.570
haven't missed a minute.
 

00:47:48.570 --> 00:47:51.239
Now it's time for you to do
your part.

00:47:51.239 --> 00:47:52.268
What's your part?
 

00:47:52.268 --> 00:47:54.340
You have to do the following
kinds of things.

00:47:54.340 --> 00:47:59.365
You have to continue to buy CDs
and download classical music off

00:47:59.365 --> 00:48:01.760
of iTunes or whatever it is.
 

00:48:01.760 --> 00:48:03.019
Don't steal that stuff.
 

00:48:03.019 --> 00:48:03.949
Why?
 

00:48:03.949 --> 00:48:06.070
If you take that stuff for
nothing, what are you doing?

00:48:06.070 --> 00:48:10.460
You're taking the livelihood
away from Jacob and Santana and

00:48:10.460 --> 00:48:13.960
Lynda here, just the livelihood
of musicians.

00:48:13.960 --> 00:48:15.710
They've put their labor into it
and you're taking it for

00:48:15.710 --> 00:48:16.030
nothing.
 

00:48:16.030 --> 00:48:17.119
So download these things.
 

00:48:17.119 --> 00:48:18.000
It doesn't cost all that much.
 

00:48:18.000 --> 00:48:19.599
Two: get involved.
 

00:48:19.599 --> 00:48:21.108
Get involved in informal
singing groups,

00:48:21.108 --> 00:48:23.199
keep your piano lessons,
if you've ever had those kinds

00:48:23.199 --> 00:48:24.708
of things going on,
local choral groups,

00:48:24.708 --> 00:48:25.289
whatever.
 

00:48:25.289 --> 00:48:26.130
You get out of Yale.
 

00:48:26.130 --> 00:48:26.929
What do you do?
 

00:48:26.929 --> 00:48:29.226
Get on the boards of these
artistic institutions,

00:48:29.226 --> 00:48:31.427
your local symphony,
your local choral society,

00:48:31.427 --> 00:48:33.820
opera company,
Neighborhood Music School here.

00:48:33.820 --> 00:48:37.230
Get on the board of that and
help them, those sorts of folks.

00:48:37.230 --> 00:48:41.452
Most important,
give music lessons to your

00:48:41.452 --> 00:48:44.438
children, adopted or natural.
 

00:48:44.438 --> 00:48:45.159
Why?
 

00:48:45.159 --> 00:48:47.858
Teaches them hard work,
teaches them to think

00:48:47.858 --> 00:48:50.396
sequentially,
teaches them various forms of

00:48:50.396 --> 00:48:53.878
quantitative reasoning,
teaches them also to be

00:48:53.878 --> 00:48:59.739
disciplined and teaches them to
have a pride in the work product

00:48:59.739 --> 00:49:02.809
that they ultimately generate.
 

00:49:02.809 --> 00:49:05.159
So these are the kinds of
things that you can do.

00:49:05.159 --> 00:49:06.699
I thank you for your attention.
 

00:49:06.699 --> 00:49:09.208
I thank you--I thank the TAs
for doing such a wonderful--and

00:49:09.208 --> 00:49:10.570
we've had great TAs this year.
 

00:49:10.570 --> 00:49:17.110
And so I will end by quoting
here Gustav Mahler once again,

00:49:17.110 --> 00:49:18.510
to share with you "meinem
Lieben,

00:49:18.510 --> 00:49:20.739
und meinem Lied,"
because it really is.

00:49:20.739 --> 00:49:22.059
